WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.437 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:03.437 --> 00:00:17.281 align:middle line:90%


00:00:17.281 --> 00:00:17.980 align:middle line:90%
Hi.

00:00:17.980 --> 00:00:21.200 align:middle line:10%
I'm Lisa Garr, host of
"Gaiam Inspirations."

00:00:21.200 --> 00:00:23.610 align:middle line:10%
Do you feel that
food controls you?

00:00:23.610 --> 00:00:25.840 align:middle line:10%
Did you know that the
brain has the same chemical

00:00:25.840 --> 00:00:27.900 align:middle line:10%
reaction to sugary
and fatty foods

00:00:27.900 --> 00:00:30.430 align:middle line:10%
that it has to
cocaine or nicotine?

00:00:30.430 --> 00:00:31.920 align:middle line:10%
And this chemical
reaction happens

00:00:31.920 --> 00:00:35.180 align:middle line:10%
even before you eat the food if
you even just think about it.

00:00:35.180 --> 00:00:37.730 align:middle line:84%
So would you like to end
that battle with food?

00:00:37.730 --> 00:00:39.680 align:middle line:84%
Today's topic is
for anyone who wants

00:00:39.680 --> 00:00:42.410 align:middle line:84%
to end the food addictions
or the hunger cravings

00:00:42.410 --> 00:00:44.540 align:middle line:90%
once and for all.

00:00:44.540 --> 00:00:46.580 align:middle line:90%
Dr. Pam Peeke is joining me.

00:00:46.580 --> 00:00:49.780 align:middle line:84%
She's a physician, scientist,
Pew Foundation scholar

00:00:49.780 --> 00:00:52.650 align:middle line:84%
in nutrition and metabolism,
and nationally renowned

00:00:52.650 --> 00:00:54.640 align:middle line:90%
expert in integrative medicine.

00:00:54.640 --> 00:00:56.970 align:middle line:84%
Dr. Peeke is a "New York
Times" best-selling author,

00:00:56.970 --> 00:00:59.320 align:middle line:84%
whose latest book
"The Hunger Fix:

00:00:59.320 --> 00:01:01.460 align:middle line:84%
the Three-Stage
Detox and Recovery

00:01:01.460 --> 00:01:04.530 align:middle line:84%
Plan for Overeating
and Food Addiction,"

00:01:04.530 --> 00:01:06.860 align:middle line:84%
it reveals that food
addiction is real.

00:01:06.860 --> 00:01:10.070 align:middle line:84%
And it's a science-based
blueprint for detox

00:01:10.070 --> 00:01:11.760 align:middle line:90%
and lifelong recovery.

00:01:11.760 --> 00:01:12.970 align:middle line:90%
Welcome to the show.

00:01:12.970 --> 00:01:14.680 align:middle line:84%
Thank you so much
for being here.

00:01:14.680 --> 00:01:16.150 align:middle line:90%
Well, hello there, Lisa.

00:01:16.150 --> 00:01:19.020 align:middle line:84%
You shed a lot of light
on this for a lot of us.

00:01:19.020 --> 00:01:21.720 align:middle line:84%
How did you first begin
to realize that food

00:01:21.720 --> 00:01:23.450 align:middle line:90%
is actually an addiction?

00:01:23.450 --> 00:01:24.360 align:middle line:90%
Well, it's interesting.

00:01:24.360 --> 00:01:25.660 align:middle line:90%
It was my patients.

00:01:25.660 --> 00:01:27.700 align:middle line:84%
They would come
in, and they would

00:01:27.700 --> 00:01:31.840 align:middle line:84%
have drug vernacular to describe
what was happening to them.

00:01:31.840 --> 00:01:33.570 align:middle line:90%
Gee, I need a hit of this.

00:01:33.570 --> 00:01:35.460 align:middle line:90%
I can't get off the stuff.

00:01:35.460 --> 00:01:37.170 align:middle line:10%
Withdrawal is killing me.

00:01:37.170 --> 00:01:39.860 align:middle line:10%
And after a while, you know,
I talked to my colleagues.

00:01:39.860 --> 00:01:41.950 align:middle line:10%
And I said, are they
all sounding like this?

00:01:41.950 --> 00:01:44.580 align:middle line:10%
And they said a growing
number of people

00:01:44.580 --> 00:01:46.720 align:middle line:10%
are really using this
kind of vernacular.

00:01:46.720 --> 00:01:48.620 align:middle line:10%
Could there be something there?

00:01:48.620 --> 00:01:51.780 align:middle line:84%
Is there a relationship
between food and addiction?

00:01:51.780 --> 00:01:53.030 align:middle line:90%
That's what got me going.

00:01:53.030 --> 00:01:56.110 align:middle line:84%
So did you ever have an
issue yourself with food?

00:01:56.110 --> 00:01:57.951 align:middle line:84%
Have you ever had
experience with being food

00:01:57.951 --> 00:02:00.110 align:middle line:84%
as an addiction?
I've said those things.

00:02:00.110 --> 00:02:01.570 align:middle line:90%
I need that cup of coffee.

00:02:01.570 --> 00:02:05.670 align:middle line:84%
Or I would die for some
sugar or for some chocolate.

00:02:05.670 --> 00:02:06.370 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:02:06.370 --> 00:02:07.590 align:middle line:90%
Lisa, please.

00:02:07.590 --> 00:02:08.350 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

00:02:08.350 --> 00:02:09.530 align:middle line:90%
OK, this is America.

00:02:09.530 --> 00:02:10.324 align:middle line:90%
All right?

00:02:10.324 --> 00:02:12.491 align:middle line:84%
If you didn't have some
kind of issue with food,

00:02:12.491 --> 00:02:14.300 align:middle line:84%
you'd be un-American.
[LAUGHTER]

00:02:14.300 --> 00:02:16.050 align:middle line:90%
So of course I've had it.

00:02:16.050 --> 00:02:18.670 align:middle line:84%
And this is another reason
why I can really relate to it.

00:02:18.670 --> 00:02:20.200 align:middle line:90%
I think all of us can.

00:02:20.200 --> 00:02:22.570 align:middle line:84%
When we sit down, close
our eyes, and say,

00:02:22.570 --> 00:02:25.350 align:middle line:84%
is there one particular
food product--

00:02:25.350 --> 00:02:27.610 align:middle line:84%
now, mind you I have
to say "food product"

00:02:27.610 --> 00:02:29.770 align:middle line:84%
because most of these
are science fair projects

00:02:29.770 --> 00:02:31.967 align:middle line:84%
or food-like products.
LISA: Mm--

00:02:31.967 --> 00:02:33.200 align:middle line:84%
So you know where
I'm going on that.

00:02:33.200 --> 00:02:34.900 align:middle line:84%
LISA: They're the most
addictive ones are those, right?

00:02:34.900 --> 00:02:36.066 align:middle line:84%
You know, close
your eyes and say,

00:02:36.066 --> 00:02:40.020 align:middle line:84%
is there one thing that I was
eating that, after I ate it,

00:02:40.020 --> 00:02:41.840 align:middle line:84%
I felt completely
out of control?

00:02:41.840 --> 00:02:43.220 align:middle line:90%
Then, you're on a bender.

00:02:43.220 --> 00:02:45.150 align:middle line:90%
And you just don't feel right.

00:02:45.150 --> 00:02:47.250 align:middle line:84%
And you're not even getting
the right satisfaction

00:02:47.250 --> 00:02:48.400 align:middle line:90%
from it anymore.

00:02:48.400 --> 00:02:50.580 align:middle line:84%
So there's something
wrong there.

00:02:50.580 --> 00:02:55.050 align:middle line:84%
So scientists began to
explore this entire arena.

00:02:55.050 --> 00:02:56.270 align:middle line:84%
So here are some
questions that you

00:02:56.270 --> 00:02:59.630 align:middle line:84%
can ask yourself to find out
if you have a food addiction.

00:02:59.630 --> 00:03:03.770 align:middle line:84%
So when life gets hard, is
it your first impulse to eat?

00:03:03.770 --> 00:03:07.560 align:middle line:10%
Do you stockpile "emergency"
snacks in your desk, closet,

00:03:07.560 --> 00:03:08.790 align:middle line:10%
or nightstand?

00:03:08.790 --> 00:03:11.640 align:middle line:10%
Do you-- do you have to know
where your next meal or food

00:03:11.640 --> 00:03:13.620 align:middle line:10%
source is going to be
at all times to feel--

00:03:13.620 --> 00:03:16.980 align:middle line:10%
or you feel nervous
or panicky or "off"?

00:03:16.980 --> 00:03:19.320 align:middle line:10%
In times of high
emotion, do you sometimes

00:03:19.320 --> 00:03:22.390 align:middle line:10%
find yourself
eating even when you

00:03:22.390 --> 00:03:24.510 align:middle line:10%
feel no physical hunger at all?

00:03:24.510 --> 00:03:26.360 align:middle line:10%
So emotional eating.

00:03:26.360 --> 00:03:28.090 align:middle line:10%
Does your relationship
with certain foods

00:03:28.090 --> 00:03:30.400 align:middle line:10%
cause you have feelings
of shame or guilt

00:03:30.400 --> 00:03:32.940 align:middle line:10%
or disgust or self-loathing?

00:03:32.940 --> 00:03:36.880 align:middle line:10%
Is food your best friend
or your worst enemy?

00:03:36.880 --> 00:03:38.740 align:middle line:10%
Actually, your best friend
and your worst enemy

00:03:38.740 --> 00:03:39.930 align:middle line:10%
at the same time.

00:03:39.930 --> 00:03:41.353 align:middle line:90%
How is that possible?

00:03:41.353 --> 00:03:45.260 align:middle line:84%
Oh, I mean, this is a rock and
a rolling kind of relationship

00:03:45.260 --> 00:03:47.360 align:middle line:90%
people have with food.

00:03:47.360 --> 00:03:49.110 align:middle line:84%
On the one hand, they
use it for comfort.

00:03:49.110 --> 00:03:50.240 align:middle line:90%
We already know that.

00:03:50.240 --> 00:03:53.170 align:middle line:84%
Actually, when you eat
these kinds of foods

00:03:53.170 --> 00:03:54.460 align:middle line:84%
that I'm talking
about, we actually

00:03:54.460 --> 00:03:57.010 align:middle line:84%
call them the
hyperpalatables, which

00:03:57.010 --> 00:04:01.290 align:middle line:84%
are the sugary, starchy,
fatty, salty combinations.

00:04:01.290 --> 00:04:05.490 align:middle line:84%
They actually, in the short
term, reduce stress hormone.

00:04:05.490 --> 00:04:09.350 align:middle line:84%
You basically go into kind of
a food numbness, an anesthetic.

00:04:09.350 --> 00:04:10.910 align:middle line:90%
But that wears off very quickly.

00:04:10.910 --> 00:04:12.040 align:middle line:90%
Then, you wake up out of it.

00:04:12.040 --> 00:04:14.500 align:middle line:84%
And you say, oh, my gosh,
what have I just done?

00:04:14.500 --> 00:04:18.070 align:middle line:84%
This is when you wake up in
bed, and you've got wrappers

00:04:18.070 --> 00:04:19.700 align:middle line:90%
and cartons all over the bed.

00:04:19.700 --> 00:04:22.089 align:middle line:84%
And you suddenly realize what
you've just done after you've

00:04:22.089 --> 00:04:23.510 align:middle line:90%
come out of your food coma.

00:04:23.510 --> 00:04:25.580 align:middle line:84%
Or you've bottomed out the
chip bag, and you realize--

00:04:25.580 --> 00:04:26.280 align:middle line:90%
DR. PEEKE: Oh, yeah.

00:04:26.280 --> 00:04:27.130 align:middle line:90%
How did I do that?

00:04:27.130 --> 00:04:30.120 align:middle line:84%
Or the other one is that
wonderful menage a trois people

00:04:30.120 --> 00:04:33.320 align:middle line:84%
have at night time,
especially women,

00:04:33.320 --> 00:04:37.140 align:middle line:84%
watching endless re-runs
of "Law and Order"

00:04:37.140 --> 00:04:38.560 align:middle line:90%
with your two best friends.

00:04:38.560 --> 00:04:42.010 align:middle line:84%
It's a menage a trois,
you, Ben, and Jerry in bed

00:04:42.010 --> 00:04:43.560 align:middle line:90%
together, all of you.

00:04:43.560 --> 00:04:44.630 align:middle line:90%
LISA: Yes.

00:04:44.630 --> 00:04:46.300 align:middle line:84%
Well, how long does
that last, though?

00:04:46.300 --> 00:04:50.190 align:middle line:84%
How long does the relaxation
part of the eating last?

00:04:50.190 --> 00:04:52.190 align:middle line:84%
Does it last for the whole
time you eat the food?

00:04:52.190 --> 00:04:53.980 align:middle line:90%
No, it's very interesting.

00:04:53.980 --> 00:04:56.955 align:middle line:84%
If you really feel
out of control

00:04:56.955 --> 00:05:01.100 align:middle line:84%
with these kinds of foods,
then you're eating with frenzy.

00:05:01.100 --> 00:05:04.080 align:middle line:84%
There's no real savoring
and really getting into it.

00:05:04.080 --> 00:05:07.620 align:middle line:84%
It's-- you're just going at
it with angst and frenzy.

00:05:07.620 --> 00:05:10.260 align:middle line:84%
So relaxation's really
not a piece of it.

00:05:10.260 --> 00:05:12.220 align:middle line:90%
What it is is numbing.

00:05:12.220 --> 00:05:14.550 align:middle line:90%
It's anesthetizing you.

00:05:14.550 --> 00:05:17.380 align:middle line:84%
So when you're stressed out
and you're feeling funky one

00:05:17.380 --> 00:05:20.020 align:middle line:84%
way or the other and
you've got these foods,

00:05:20.020 --> 00:05:21.920 align:middle line:84%
you know, flying
through your mouth,

00:05:21.920 --> 00:05:26.020 align:middle line:84%
then you just go from
angst to numb, basically.

00:05:26.020 --> 00:05:28.040 align:middle line:84%
So let's talk about some
of the science around this.

00:05:28.040 --> 00:05:29.650 align:middle line:84%
What does the
brain actually look

00:05:29.650 --> 00:05:32.390 align:middle line:84%
like on these food addictions?
-OK.

00:05:32.390 --> 00:05:34.310 align:middle line:84%
Well, for the longest
period of time,

00:05:34.310 --> 00:05:37.980 align:middle line:84%
scientists have really
wanted to explore

00:05:37.980 --> 00:05:39.920 align:middle line:84%
that one part of the
brain that we know

00:05:39.920 --> 00:05:43.420 align:middle line:84%
is already affected by
drugs, for instance,

00:05:43.420 --> 00:05:47.140 align:middle line:84%
and alcohol, so as it
were, validated addictions.

00:05:47.140 --> 00:05:49.220 align:middle line:84%
And that's the reward
center of the brain.

00:05:49.220 --> 00:05:51.560 align:middle line:10%
When you look at brain scans,
what you'll actually find

00:05:51.560 --> 00:05:54.790 align:middle line:10%
is if you look at a binge
eater, for instance, as compared

00:05:54.790 --> 00:05:57.260 align:middle line:10%
to someone who doesn't
binge, and you actually just

00:05:57.260 --> 00:06:01.490 align:middle line:10%
give them the simple cue
that a food is actually

00:06:01.490 --> 00:06:03.290 align:middle line:10%
coming or just the sight of it.

00:06:03.290 --> 00:06:04.770 align:middle line:10%
But they haven't
even eaten it yet.

00:06:04.770 --> 00:06:09.100 align:middle line:10%
What you're actually noticing is
the red there is the dopamine.

00:06:09.100 --> 00:06:13.040 align:middle line:10%
And that is the neurotransmitter
that is associated with reward

00:06:13.040 --> 00:06:14.670 align:middle line:10%
and pleasure in the brain.

00:06:14.670 --> 00:06:16.840 align:middle line:10%
The dopamine in
the control subject

00:06:16.840 --> 00:06:18.630 align:middle line:10%
is basically pretty normal.

00:06:18.630 --> 00:06:21.060 align:middle line:10%
They have a little bit
more dopamine coming up.

00:06:21.060 --> 00:06:22.110 align:middle line:10%
They're excited.

00:06:22.110 --> 00:06:22.810 align:middle line:10%
They see it.

00:06:22.810 --> 00:06:24.440 align:middle line:10%
But if you look at
the binge eater,

00:06:24.440 --> 00:06:27.250 align:middle line:10%
wow, the dopamine
just disappears as

00:06:27.250 --> 00:06:29.570 align:middle line:10%
soon as they've seen that food.

00:06:29.570 --> 00:06:31.060 align:middle line:10%
And that is because,
one, they've

00:06:31.060 --> 00:06:33.160 align:middle line:10%
been hyperconditioned to it.

00:06:33.160 --> 00:06:36.990 align:middle line:84%
And two, because they don't
even secrete that much.

00:06:36.990 --> 00:06:40.480 align:middle line:84%
They don't even have that
many dopamine receptors

00:06:40.480 --> 00:06:43.730 align:middle line:84%
to be able to pick it
up because over time,

00:06:43.730 --> 00:06:46.030 align:middle line:90%
that entire system changes.

00:06:46.030 --> 00:06:47.291 align:middle line:84%
So when someone
sees a commercial--

00:06:47.291 --> 00:06:47.990 align:middle line:90%
[SIGH]

00:06:47.990 --> 00:06:50.480 align:middle line:84%
When someone sees a
billboard, this reaction

00:06:50.480 --> 00:06:51.490 align:middle line:90%
happens in the brain.

00:06:51.490 --> 00:06:52.223 align:middle line:90%
DR. PEEKE: Absolutely.

00:06:52.223 --> 00:06:55.790 align:middle line:84%
It could even be looking
at someone who you usually

00:06:55.790 --> 00:06:58.020 align:middle line:90%
hang out with when you overeat.

00:06:58.020 --> 00:06:59.780 align:middle line:90%
It could be that subtle.

00:06:59.780 --> 00:07:02.750 align:middle line:84%
The cues are everywhere
in our environment.

00:07:02.750 --> 00:07:04.910 align:middle line:84%
It could be the chair
you're sitting in.

00:07:04.910 --> 00:07:07.790 align:middle line:84%
Maybe that's the chair
you always have binges in.

00:07:07.790 --> 00:07:09.100 align:middle line:90%
What if I think about it?

00:07:09.100 --> 00:07:10.659 align:middle line:84%
-That's all it is.
-You're kidding.

00:07:10.659 --> 00:07:11.740 align:middle line:90%
It's just a thought.

00:07:11.740 --> 00:07:14.230 align:middle line:84%
That's how powerful
these cues are.

00:07:14.230 --> 00:07:16.430 align:middle line:84%
The reward center
in the brain is

00:07:16.430 --> 00:07:18.700 align:middle line:90%
exquisitely sensitive to this.

00:07:18.700 --> 00:07:22.520 align:middle line:84%
And so dopamine gets secreted
immediately in response

00:07:22.520 --> 00:07:24.720 align:middle line:84%
to these kinds of
cues, especially

00:07:24.720 --> 00:07:28.340 align:middle line:84%
in people like binge eaters,
compulsive eaters, and people

00:07:28.340 --> 00:07:29.640 align:middle line:90%
who are addicted to food.

00:07:29.640 --> 00:07:32.740 align:middle line:84%
So the dopamine is the
feel-good element of the brain?

00:07:32.740 --> 00:07:35.330 align:middle line:84%
Is that what makes
us feel high or good?

00:07:35.330 --> 00:07:37.570 align:middle line:90%
Dopamine is a neurotransmitter.

00:07:37.570 --> 00:07:41.010 align:middle line:84%
It's a brain chemical that
is associated with anything

00:07:41.010 --> 00:07:42.880 align:middle line:90%
that has to do with reward.

00:07:42.880 --> 00:07:45.160 align:middle line:84%
It helps you with
motivation for reward.

00:07:45.160 --> 00:07:47.660 align:middle line:84%
You want to get
that college degree.

00:07:47.660 --> 00:07:51.400 align:middle line:84%
It gives you short term
gratification, long term.

00:07:51.400 --> 00:07:52.360 align:middle line:90%
It doesn't matter.

00:07:52.360 --> 00:07:56.500 align:middle line:84%
Anything that has to do with
reward, promoting reward

00:07:56.500 --> 00:07:58.070 align:middle line:90%
is all about dopamine.

00:07:58.070 --> 00:07:59.750 align:middle line:90%
Dopamine's in charge of that.

00:07:59.750 --> 00:08:02.590 align:middle line:84%
And then, the receptors
receive the dopamine.

00:08:02.590 --> 00:08:04.690 align:middle line:84%
So if there's a
cascade or a flood--

00:08:04.690 --> 00:08:06.810 align:middle line:84%
or you give the analogy
in the book, which I think

00:08:06.810 --> 00:08:09.781 align:middle line:84%
was brilliant, of a
flood going down a river.

00:08:09.781 --> 00:08:10.480 align:middle line:90%
DR. PEEKE: Mm-hm.

00:08:10.480 --> 00:08:14.550 align:middle line:84%
And it overcomes the river
and goes over the bank.

00:08:14.550 --> 00:08:17.311 align:middle line:84%
So it blows out, say, the
dopamine receptor for trees.

00:08:17.311 --> 00:08:18.830 align:middle line:84%
Right?
DR. PEEKE: That's right.

00:08:18.830 --> 00:08:23.050 align:middle line:84%
Well, so what ends up happening
in the brain of someone who

00:08:23.050 --> 00:08:26.810 align:middle line:84%
is at first-- let's just
say right off the bat,

00:08:26.810 --> 00:08:28.690 align:middle line:90%
you came from Amazon.

00:08:28.690 --> 00:08:30.320 align:middle line:84%
And now, you're gonna
come to America,

00:08:30.320 --> 00:08:33.679 align:middle line:84%
and you're gonna find sugary,
fatty, starchy, salty,

00:08:33.679 --> 00:08:35.530 align:middle line:84%
substances everywhere.
Right?

00:08:35.530 --> 00:08:39.700 align:middle line:84%
And so suddenly, these are
real hyperpalatable rewards.

00:08:39.700 --> 00:08:43.230 align:middle line:84%
Lots and lots of dopamine
starts being secreted.

00:08:43.230 --> 00:08:46.570 align:middle line:84%
So much so, over a period of
time-- not just once, but over

00:08:46.570 --> 00:08:49.680 align:middle line:84%
a period of time-- that
your receptors which

00:08:49.680 --> 00:08:51.940 align:middle line:84%
have to manage all
of this dopamine

00:08:51.940 --> 00:08:55.650 align:middle line:84%
basically become
absolutely overwhelmed.

00:08:55.650 --> 00:08:59.630 align:middle line:84%
The brain realizes it can't
process this amount of dopamine

00:08:59.630 --> 00:09:00.960 align:middle line:90%
coming in, that river.

00:09:00.960 --> 00:09:02.530 align:middle line:90%
It can't process it.

00:09:02.530 --> 00:09:05.660 align:middle line:84%
So instead, it takes
the actual receptors,

00:09:05.660 --> 00:09:08.370 align:middle line:84%
and it does something
we call downregulating.

00:09:08.370 --> 00:09:09.380 align:middle line:90%
What does it mean?

00:09:09.380 --> 00:09:11.640 align:middle line:84%
It means it turns
off and deactivates

00:09:11.640 --> 00:09:13.060 align:middle line:90%
most of these receptors.

00:09:13.060 --> 00:09:15.870 align:middle line:84%
So now, someone who
has an addiction,

00:09:15.870 --> 00:09:19.930 align:middle line:84%
whether it's alcohol, cocaine,
meth, or food-- right?

00:09:19.930 --> 00:09:21.880 align:middle line:90%
They have fewer receptors.

00:09:21.880 --> 00:09:23.860 align:middle line:84%
These are called D2 receptors.
-Ah.

00:09:23.860 --> 00:09:26.520 align:middle line:84%
We can actually
see this on scans.

00:09:26.520 --> 00:09:28.030 align:middle line:84%
So what this does
is the brain actually

00:09:28.030 --> 00:09:29.789 align:middle line:84%
turns against you then.
Right?

00:09:29.789 --> 00:09:31.020 align:middle line:84%
Well, what it
does is it doesn't

00:09:31.020 --> 00:09:32.600 align:middle line:90%
understand what's happening.

00:09:32.600 --> 00:09:37.050 align:middle line:84%
Everything in the brain is all
geared to one thing, Lisa--

00:09:37.050 --> 00:09:38.510 align:middle line:90%
survival.

00:09:38.510 --> 00:09:40.310 align:middle line:84%
And so if it sees
that you're getting

00:09:40.310 --> 00:09:44.810 align:middle line:84%
this huge rush all the time,
it tries to control this.

00:09:44.810 --> 00:09:46.970 align:middle line:84%
And it controls this
by downregulating

00:09:46.970 --> 00:09:50.530 align:middle line:84%
those dopamine receptors so
that you don't get overwhelmed.

00:09:50.530 --> 00:09:55.490 align:middle line:84%
What unfortunately happens
is you start a vicious cycle.

00:09:55.490 --> 00:09:58.870 align:middle line:84%
Because now, when I want to get
re-exposed to that particular

00:09:58.870 --> 00:10:02.550 align:middle line:84%
food stuff-- let's just say that
cupcake rolls around again--

00:10:02.550 --> 00:10:04.120 align:middle line:90%
then I eat the cupcake.

00:10:04.120 --> 00:10:06.140 align:middle line:84%
I even see the cue
for the cupcake.

00:10:06.140 --> 00:10:08.840 align:middle line:84%
But I'm not feeling
as much reward

00:10:08.840 --> 00:10:13.970 align:middle line:84%
because the dopamine receptors
are decreased in number.

00:10:13.970 --> 00:10:16.210 align:middle line:84%
And I'm not getting
as much reward.

00:10:16.210 --> 00:10:17.400 align:middle line:90%
So guess what happens?

00:10:17.400 --> 00:10:18.310 align:middle line:90%
You guessed it.

00:10:18.310 --> 00:10:21.360 align:middle line:84%
I have to have not
one, but five cupcakes

00:10:21.360 --> 00:10:24.810 align:middle line:84%
to get the same reward
I got originally.

00:10:24.810 --> 00:10:26.259 align:middle line:84%
LISA: Huh.
So this--

00:10:26.259 --> 00:10:28.660 align:middle line:84%
And it's-- well, this is the
same thing happens in drugs.

00:10:28.660 --> 00:10:31.830 align:middle line:84%
One moment, you have just one
hit of crack or, you know--

00:10:31.830 --> 00:10:32.690 align:middle line:90%
Mm.

00:10:32.690 --> 00:10:33.820 align:middle line:90%
Or heroine.

00:10:33.820 --> 00:10:36.650 align:middle line:84%
The next time, you're
just running at it.

00:10:36.650 --> 00:10:38.770 align:middle line:84%
So what the brain
looks-- this is

00:10:38.770 --> 00:10:40.040 align:middle line:84%
a-- we actually
have a slide here

00:10:40.040 --> 00:10:41.306 align:middle line:84%
of what the brain
looks like when it's

00:10:41.306 --> 00:10:43.100 align:middle line:90%
swelled with this dopamine.

00:10:43.100 --> 00:10:44.000 align:middle line:90%
Is this what it looks like?

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:46.800 align:middle line:84%
DR. PEEKE: OK, well, so
this is a beautiful picture

00:10:46.800 --> 00:10:47.850 align:middle line:90%
of the brain.

00:10:47.850 --> 00:10:49.990 align:middle line:84%
And what we're looking
at here is how much

00:10:49.990 --> 00:10:54.210 align:middle line:90%
the brain enhances expectation.

00:10:54.210 --> 00:10:56.960 align:middle line:84%
So remember how I told
you about the cue.

00:10:56.960 --> 00:10:59.510 align:middle line:84%
All I have to say is, you
know, in about two hours, Lisa,

00:10:59.510 --> 00:11:01.360 align:middle line:90%
we're gonna have a cupcake.

00:11:01.360 --> 00:11:03.580 align:middle line:84%
Or and if that turns out
to be something that's

00:11:03.580 --> 00:11:06.230 align:middle line:84%
one of your binge-able,
cravable, what

00:11:06.230 --> 00:11:08.620 align:middle line:84%
I love to call "false fixes."
All right?

00:11:08.620 --> 00:11:11.060 align:middle line:84%
So what ends up
happening is you suddenly

00:11:11.060 --> 00:11:13.580 align:middle line:84%
realize that where that
orange is just lit up,

00:11:13.580 --> 00:11:17.580 align:middle line:84%
turned on, that you have
dopamine flooding in,

00:11:17.580 --> 00:11:19.910 align:middle line:90%
enhancing expectation.

00:11:19.910 --> 00:11:22.260 align:middle line:84%
And then, the
question by scientists

00:11:22.260 --> 00:11:23.740 align:middle line:84%
in this one
particular experiment

00:11:23.740 --> 00:11:28.050 align:middle line:84%
was how long does
that expectation last?

00:11:28.050 --> 00:11:29.860 align:middle line:84%
How long can you
keep that dopamine

00:11:29.860 --> 00:11:31.730 align:middle line:90%
enhancing that feeling?

00:11:31.730 --> 00:11:32.750 align:middle line:90%
Guess what?

00:11:32.750 --> 00:11:36.570 align:middle line:84%
80% of the subjects
in the experiment

00:11:36.570 --> 00:11:40.720 align:middle line:84%
kept it going for 24 hours.
-After they--

00:11:40.720 --> 00:11:42.420 align:middle line:84%
-It just keeps going and going--
-Oh, my goodness.

00:11:42.420 --> 00:11:42.920 align:middle line:90%
 --and going.

00:11:42.920 --> 00:11:45.084 align:middle line:84%
So this isn't one of those, oh,
wow, what a wonderful thought.

00:11:45.084 --> 00:11:46.550 align:middle line:84%
And then, it just, you
know, flittered off--

00:11:46.550 --> 00:11:47.660 align:middle line:84%
-Right.
- --and ended.

00:11:47.660 --> 00:11:48.359 align:middle line:90%
No.

00:11:48.359 --> 00:11:50.430 align:middle line:84%
This can keep-- this
is why people obsess.

00:11:50.430 --> 00:11:52.830 align:middle line:84%
This explains the
epidemic that we have

00:11:52.830 --> 00:11:54.670 align:middle line:90%
in this country of obesity.

00:11:54.670 --> 00:11:56.860 align:middle line:84%
Yes, this explains the
trouble that we're in.

00:11:56.860 --> 00:11:59.290 align:middle line:84%
Because it is a
chemical reaction.

00:11:59.290 --> 00:12:02.370 align:middle line:84%
But most people wouldn't
think of food as a drug.

00:12:02.370 --> 00:12:06.770 align:middle line:84%
Well, now, you see, I'll betcha
people watching this interview

00:12:06.770 --> 00:12:08.931 align:middle line:84%
would say, I'm not an addict.
You know?

00:12:08.931 --> 00:12:09.630 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:09.630 --> 00:12:11.630 align:middle line:84%
And you have all these terrible
thoughts about, you know,

00:12:11.630 --> 00:12:14.620 align:middle line:84%
addicts in, you know, the
end of allies or something.

00:12:14.620 --> 00:12:17.290 align:middle line:84%
And yet, at the same
time, how many of you

00:12:17.290 --> 00:12:18.860 align:middle line:84%
have fished through
a garbage can,

00:12:18.860 --> 00:12:21.250 align:middle line:84%
you know, to find
that cupcake again.

00:12:21.250 --> 00:12:26.420 align:middle line:84%
No, but seriously, as it
turns out, in all seriousness,

00:12:26.420 --> 00:12:28.990 align:middle line:84%
at the National
Institutes of Health all

00:12:28.990 --> 00:12:31.960 align:middle line:84%
throughout the world, we've
been looking at the science

00:12:31.960 --> 00:12:33.750 align:middle line:90%
of food and addiction.

00:12:33.750 --> 00:12:35.670 align:middle line:84%
And we finally hit
a tipping point.

00:12:35.670 --> 00:12:39.920 align:middle line:84%
We realized that through all
of the new tools that we have,

00:12:39.920 --> 00:12:43.500 align:middle line:84%
the PET scans, the functional
MRIs, and all of these lovely

00:12:43.500 --> 00:12:46.540 align:middle line:84%
scans that you've been
seeing, that we now understand

00:12:46.540 --> 00:12:49.900 align:middle line:84%
that there is a very
striking relationship

00:12:49.900 --> 00:12:51.550 align:middle line:90%
between food and addiction.

00:12:51.550 --> 00:12:54.020 align:middle line:84%
And for that matter,
the same centers

00:12:54.020 --> 00:12:59.820 align:middle line:84%
of the brain that regulate drug
addiction also regulate food.

00:12:59.820 --> 00:13:01.490 align:middle line:90%
Now, that's what's shocking.

00:13:01.490 --> 00:13:02.950 align:middle line:84%
And food is
available everywhere.

00:13:02.950 --> 00:13:03.650 align:middle line:90%
DR. PEEKE: Well--

00:13:03.650 --> 00:13:05.510 align:middle line:90%
You know, drugs are illegal.

00:13:05.510 --> 00:13:06.970 align:middle line:90%
But the food is everywhere.

00:13:06.970 --> 00:13:09.460 align:middle line:84%
So it makes it more
tempting and more

00:13:09.460 --> 00:13:12.210 align:middle line:90%
up to us to use will power.

00:13:12.210 --> 00:13:14.640 align:middle line:84%
DR. PEEKE: Well, you see,
here's another issue.

00:13:14.640 --> 00:13:16.340 align:middle line:90%
And we'll be getting into this.

00:13:16.340 --> 00:13:20.640 align:middle line:84%
But in your brain,
there's a battle going on.

00:13:20.640 --> 00:13:23.780 align:middle line:84%
You've got the reward
system that's been hijacked

00:13:23.780 --> 00:13:26.580 align:middle line:84%
by these hyperpalatables.
Because come on.

00:13:26.580 --> 00:13:28.470 align:middle line:84%
I mean, let's just get
real here for a minute.

00:13:28.470 --> 00:13:31.700 align:middle line:84%
You got a bowl of berries,
fresh berries, whole foods.

00:13:31.700 --> 00:13:34.960 align:middle line:84%
And then, you've got
this huge, steaming,

00:13:34.960 --> 00:13:39.550 align:middle line:84%
wonderful, warm, strawberry
tart with a cream

00:13:39.550 --> 00:13:41.490 align:middle line:84%
center and all the gooey--
[LAUGHTER]

00:13:41.490 --> 00:13:42.889 align:middle line:84%
Give me a break.
[LAUGHTER]

00:13:42.889 --> 00:13:44.130 align:middle line:84%
Who do you think--
I mean, come on.

00:13:44.130 --> 00:13:45.260 align:middle line:84%
Let's get real
here for a minute.

00:13:45.260 --> 00:13:45.540 align:middle line:90%
Uh-huh.

00:13:45.540 --> 00:13:47.507 align:middle line:84%
So I mean, don't think for
a second the food industry

00:13:47.507 --> 00:13:48.820 align:middle line:84%
hasn't figured this out either.
-Right.

00:13:48.820 --> 00:13:50.460 align:middle line:84%
Right.
-So there it is.

00:13:50.460 --> 00:13:53.670 align:middle line:84%
And then you say,
well, gosh, is everyone

00:13:53.670 --> 00:13:55.440 align:middle line:90%
affected by food addiction?

00:13:55.440 --> 00:13:58.130 align:middle line:90%
I would say not everyone.

00:13:58.130 --> 00:14:00.630 align:middle line:84%
I would probably say
the majority of people.

00:14:00.630 --> 00:14:03.420 align:middle line:84%
And there's a wide
spectrum of, you know,

00:14:03.420 --> 00:14:05.710 align:middle line:84%
people who have a
mild food addiction

00:14:05.710 --> 00:14:10.400 align:middle line:84%
to people who have very striking
and serious food addiction.

00:14:10.400 --> 00:14:15.320 align:middle line:84%
And these people also tend to
be cross-addicted, many of them,

00:14:15.320 --> 00:14:17.870 align:middle line:84%
meaning they have
other addictions

00:14:17.870 --> 00:14:20.560 align:middle line:84%
both genetically and
otherwise, like alcohol,

00:14:20.560 --> 00:14:23.620 align:middle line:84%
cigarettes, drugs.
LISA: Interesting.

00:14:23.620 --> 00:14:26.230 align:middle line:84%
So there's-- it's not
just the food addiction.

00:14:26.230 --> 00:14:28.340 align:middle line:84%
It goes generationally,
which is also--

00:14:28.340 --> 00:14:29.860 align:middle line:84%
Well, you've got--
all of a sudden,

00:14:29.860 --> 00:14:33.840 align:middle line:84%
you've got this cross-linking
between all of these addictions

00:14:33.840 --> 00:14:38.020 align:middle line:84%
that just sort of increases
the intensity of all addictions

00:14:38.020 --> 00:14:40.990 align:middle line:84%
by an order of magnitude
over people who just

00:14:40.990 --> 00:14:42.200 align:middle line:90%
simply have food addiction.

00:14:42.200 --> 00:14:43.535 align:middle line:84%
LISA: So we have
a slide about that

00:14:43.535 --> 00:14:46.014 align:middle line:84%
that shows the cross-linking
that you're talking about.

00:14:46.014 --> 00:14:47.680 align:middle line:84%
DR. PEEKE: Well, actually,
you know, what this one

00:14:47.680 --> 00:14:48.830 align:middle line:90%
is is very interesting.

00:14:48.830 --> 00:14:52.700 align:middle line:84%
This is a slide that shows the
brain, one of those centers

00:14:52.700 --> 00:14:54.790 align:middle line:84%
of the brain in
the reward center

00:14:54.790 --> 00:14:58.390 align:middle line:84%
that also is highly
associated with overeating.

00:14:58.390 --> 00:15:02.230 align:middle line:84%
So we decided to look
at an animal experiment

00:15:02.230 --> 00:15:05.520 align:middle line:84%
to see whether or not there
was any cross-linking between

00:15:05.520 --> 00:15:07.870 align:middle line:90%
overeating and cocaine abuse.

00:15:07.870 --> 00:15:11.860 align:middle line:84%
And as it turns out, it's
either one or the other.

00:15:11.860 --> 00:15:13.890 align:middle line:84%
You can't have both
at the same time.

00:15:13.890 --> 00:15:16.090 align:middle line:84%
When you stimulate
for food, what

00:15:16.090 --> 00:15:19.870 align:middle line:84%
you see is a decrease in
interest in both cocaine

00:15:19.870 --> 00:15:24.060 align:middle line:84%
as well as what we call
"novelty behavior,"

00:15:24.060 --> 00:15:27.970 align:middle line:84%
meaning that you want-- you're
exploring your environment.

00:15:27.970 --> 00:15:29.420 align:middle line:90%
You're taking risks.

00:15:29.420 --> 00:15:32.160 align:middle line:84%
So taking risk and
cocaine go together.

00:15:32.160 --> 00:15:36.440 align:middle line:84%
When those are stimulated, food
and appetite are decreased.

00:15:36.440 --> 00:15:38.050 align:middle line:90%
It's either one or the other.

00:15:38.050 --> 00:15:41.280 align:middle line:10%
But they're happening at the
same center in the brain,

00:15:41.280 --> 00:15:42.810 align:middle line:10%
which we never knew.

00:15:42.810 --> 00:15:46.940 align:middle line:84%
So the brain is either seeking
food or it's taking risk.

00:15:46.940 --> 00:15:49.380 align:middle line:84%
But it's not seeking the food
and the risk at the same time.

00:15:49.380 --> 00:15:50.080 align:middle line:90%
That's right.

00:15:50.080 --> 00:15:54.320 align:middle line:84%
And the risk is most highly
associated with drugs and drug

00:15:54.320 --> 00:15:56.770 align:middle line:90%
addiction, not with food.

00:15:56.770 --> 00:15:59.360 align:middle line:84%
Could you say that
the brain could

00:15:59.360 --> 00:16:05.120 align:middle line:84%
be interested in goal
setting or pleasure--

00:16:05.120 --> 00:16:09.760 align:middle line:84%
other types of pleasures and
not be interested in food

00:16:09.760 --> 00:16:10.540 align:middle line:90%
at the same time?

00:16:10.540 --> 00:16:13.021 align:middle line:84%
So if you say you want to go
out and play with your child.

00:16:13.021 --> 00:16:13.720 align:middle line:90%
DR. PEEKE: Of course.

00:16:13.720 --> 00:16:15.170 align:middle line:84%
Does that decrease
your desire for food?

00:16:15.170 --> 00:16:16.003 align:middle line:90%
DR. PEEKE: Oh, no, no no.

00:16:16.003 --> 00:16:18.520 align:middle line:84%
See what happens here is
you're-- you know, that

00:16:18.520 --> 00:16:20.440 align:middle line:90%
question is excellent, Lisa.

00:16:20.440 --> 00:16:23.490 align:middle line:84%
Because when you're
playing with your daughter

00:16:23.490 --> 00:16:25.780 align:middle line:84%
and you're having so much fun,
the last thing on your mind

00:16:25.780 --> 00:16:26.040 align:middle line:84%
is--
LISA: Right.

00:16:26.040 --> 00:16:27.560 align:middle line:84%
 --hey, man, I need
to score a candy bar.

00:16:27.560 --> 00:16:29.310 align:middle line:84%
LISA: Exactly.
-It just doesn't happen.

00:16:29.310 --> 00:16:32.760 align:middle line:84%
Because now, you-- actually,
it's the reason why I called it

00:16:32.760 --> 00:16:33.950 align:middle line:90%
"The Hunger Fix."

00:16:33.950 --> 00:16:36.740 align:middle line:84%
What do you really hunger for?
-Mm.

00:16:36.740 --> 00:16:39.090 align:middle line:84%
And what you want is
a rich, wonderful life,

00:16:39.090 --> 00:16:40.230 align:middle line:90%
like enjoying your daughter.

00:16:40.230 --> 00:16:41.030 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:16:41.030 --> 00:16:44.380 align:middle line:84%
Instead of the false
hungers of the food

00:16:44.380 --> 00:16:46.830 align:middle line:84%
addictions which
drag you from that.

00:16:46.830 --> 00:16:51.060 align:middle line:84%
Because what we found, in both
animal experiments and human,

00:16:51.060 --> 00:16:54.790 align:middle line:84%
when you're in full
on, blowout addiction,

00:16:54.790 --> 00:16:57.110 align:middle line:84%
you don't care
about your family.

00:16:57.110 --> 00:16:59.520 align:middle line:84%
You don't care about
your obligations

00:16:59.520 --> 00:17:00.960 align:middle line:90%
and responsibilities.

00:17:00.960 --> 00:17:02.800 align:middle line:90%
You don't care about your work.

00:17:02.800 --> 00:17:04.050 align:middle line:90%
You don't care about self-care.

00:17:04.050 --> 00:17:04.800 align:middle line:90%
LISA: Mm.

00:17:04.800 --> 00:17:07.210 align:middle line:84%
You let it all
go for one thing.

00:17:07.210 --> 00:17:10.630 align:middle line:84%
And that is the foraging to
be able to find that food.

00:17:10.630 --> 00:17:13.730 align:middle line:84%
For that matter, in
animal experiments,

00:17:13.730 --> 00:17:18.200 align:middle line:84%
if we electrified the floor and
we had the hyperpalatable food

00:17:18.200 --> 00:17:20.530 align:middle line:84%
that they got conditioned
to on the other side

00:17:20.530 --> 00:17:24.710 align:middle line:84%
of that electrified floor,
these animals don't care.

00:17:24.710 --> 00:17:26.654 align:middle line:84%
They'll come right
across, get injured--

00:17:26.654 --> 00:17:27.500 align:middle line:90%
LISA: Oh.

00:17:27.500 --> 00:17:31.580 align:middle line:84%
 --in the seeking for this
because they want it that much.

00:17:31.580 --> 00:17:34.480 align:middle line:84%
And boy, I'll tell you there's
some people watching this right

00:17:34.480 --> 00:17:37.050 align:middle line:84%
now who could raise their
hand and say, been there, done

00:17:37.050 --> 00:17:38.570 align:middle line:84%
that, probably
doing it right now.

00:17:38.570 --> 00:17:40.100 align:middle line:84%
LISA: I would--
yes, yes, exactly.

00:17:40.100 --> 00:17:41.640 align:middle line:90%
Get electrified for food.

00:17:41.640 --> 00:17:44.420 align:middle line:84%
It's interesting, though,
because when you exercise

00:17:44.420 --> 00:17:48.030 align:middle line:84%
or when you work out, you
always say, oh, I'm not hungry.

00:17:48.030 --> 00:17:51.770 align:middle line:84%
You know it's-- you don't
feel hungry if you're finding

00:17:51.770 --> 00:17:54.430 align:middle line:84%
something that excites you or
is interesting to you, even

00:17:54.430 --> 00:17:56.170 align:middle line:90%
if it's exercising or playing.

00:17:56.170 --> 00:17:59.010 align:middle line:84%
Let me ask you about
putting up, say, pictures

00:17:59.010 --> 00:18:00.750 align:middle line:90%
