possibly do is try to teach

00:52:24.530 --> 00:52:28.260 align:middle line:84%
that child how to
be able to discern

00:52:28.260 --> 00:52:30.130 align:middle line:90%
what's good and what isn't.

00:52:30.130 --> 00:52:31.827 align:middle line:84%
You know, kids can do this.
They're smart.

00:52:31.827 --> 00:52:32.760 align:middle line:90%
They're little smarty pants.

00:52:32.760 --> 00:52:33.950 align:middle line:90%
LISA: They know what's healthy.

00:52:33.950 --> 00:52:35.090 align:middle line:90%
And you know what you do?

00:52:35.090 --> 00:52:37.430 align:middle line:84%
You get them involved
in growing gardens.

00:52:37.430 --> 00:52:40.140 align:middle line:84%
Kids decrease the
amount of trash

00:52:40.140 --> 00:52:43.180 align:middle line:84%
they eat when they grow
their own garden because they

00:52:43.180 --> 00:52:44.550 align:middle line:90%
make the connection.

00:52:44.550 --> 00:52:45.490 align:middle line:90%
They get it.

00:52:45.490 --> 00:52:48.256 align:middle line:10%
And they have great pride
when they grew that, you know,

00:52:48.256 --> 00:52:48.955 align:middle line:10%
watermelon.

00:52:48.955 --> 00:52:50.720 align:middle line:84%
And they are gonna
be able to eat it

00:52:50.720 --> 00:52:52.280 align:middle line:90%
and share it with other people.

00:52:52.280 --> 00:52:55.910 align:middle line:84%
Get them involved with the
entire cooking process.

00:52:55.910 --> 00:52:58.220 align:middle line:84%
Get them involved
with food preparation,

00:52:58.220 --> 00:53:00.240 align:middle line:84%
with food-- grocery
shopping, for instance.

00:53:00.240 --> 00:53:01.135 align:middle line:90%
Whole food preparation.

00:53:01.135 --> 00:53:02.200 align:middle line:90%
Get it going.

00:53:02.200 --> 00:53:04.430 align:middle line:84%
Make them part of
the entire cycle.

00:53:04.430 --> 00:53:08.640 align:middle line:84%
Right now, today's children
are so disassociated from all

00:53:08.640 --> 00:53:12.490 align:middle line:84%
of that entire world of food
preparation, development,

00:53:12.490 --> 00:53:13.890 align:middle line:90%
growing, the rest of it.

00:53:13.890 --> 00:53:15.820 align:middle line:90%
Bring them back in again.

00:53:15.820 --> 00:53:18.800 align:middle line:84%
And that means that the
parents have to be engaged.

00:53:18.800 --> 00:53:20.530 align:middle line:84%
And if the parents
aren't engaged,

00:53:20.530 --> 00:53:23.030 align:middle line:90%
the children will follow suit.

00:53:23.030 --> 00:53:24.950 align:middle line:84%
Well, that is
actually a great tip

00:53:24.950 --> 00:53:27.120 align:middle line:84%
is to get the children
involved in growing food

00:53:27.120 --> 00:53:29.840 align:middle line:84%
and in making the food
in the kitchen as well.

00:53:29.840 --> 00:53:32.450 align:middle line:84%
And when they get out
into the world-- I mean,

00:53:32.450 --> 00:53:35.160 align:middle line:84%
I have a gluten free lifestyle
and so does my daughter.

00:53:35.160 --> 00:53:37.490 align:middle line:84%
When she gets to
school, it's sandwiches,

00:53:37.490 --> 00:53:39.410 align:middle line:90%
pizza, breaded chicken.

00:53:39.410 --> 00:53:41.360 align:middle line:84%
It's everything that's--
DR. PEEKE: I know.

00:53:41.360 --> 00:53:44.780 align:middle line:84%
You know, so she has
to, at a young age,

00:53:44.780 --> 00:53:46.470 align:middle line:90%
learn self discipline.

00:53:46.470 --> 00:53:48.180 align:middle line:84%
But at the same
time, I don't want

00:53:48.180 --> 00:53:49.914 align:middle line:90%
to give her a complex about it.

00:53:49.914 --> 00:53:51.479 align:middle line:84%
I don't want to give her--
DR. PEEKE: No.

00:53:51.479 --> 00:53:54.081 align:middle line:84%
 --an eating disorder by
having her focus too much on it.

00:53:54.081 --> 00:53:54.780 align:middle line:90%
You know something?

00:53:54.780 --> 00:53:59.231 align:middle line:84%
Your problem and your challenge
is shared by so many parents

00:53:59.231 --> 00:54:00.220 align:middle line:84%
out there.
-Yes.

00:54:00.220 --> 00:54:01.840 align:middle line:84%
And my heart goes
out to all of you

00:54:01.840 --> 00:54:05.160 align:middle line:84%
because this is so much
harder than when we grew up.

00:54:05.160 --> 00:54:08.970 align:middle line:84%
When I grew up, I mean, my snack
after I came home from school

00:54:08.970 --> 00:54:11.180 align:middle line:90%
were graham crackers and fruit.

00:54:11.180 --> 00:54:12.530 align:middle line:90%
It was sort of simple.

00:54:12.530 --> 00:54:17.220 align:middle line:84%
Now, you know, it's like a whole
panoply of hyperpalatables.

00:54:17.220 --> 00:54:19.700 align:middle line:84%
And the poor kids don't
know which way is up.

00:54:19.700 --> 00:54:22.610 align:middle line:84%
And they think it's cool to
have the hyperpalatables.

00:54:22.610 --> 00:54:23.680 align:middle line:90%
We have to sit down.

00:54:23.680 --> 00:54:25.860 align:middle line:84%
And we've got to,
in a loving way,

00:54:25.860 --> 00:54:29.450 align:middle line:84%
not in food policing at
all, but in a loving way,

00:54:29.450 --> 00:54:32.700 align:middle line:84%
teach them by
mentoring ourselves,

00:54:32.700 --> 00:54:36.320 align:middle line:84%
by being good role
models, and engaging them,

00:54:36.320 --> 00:54:38.320 align:middle line:84%
participating in
the entire thing.

00:54:38.320 --> 00:54:43.180 align:middle line:84%
Because if we don't, we're going
to be raising full generations

00:54:43.180 --> 00:54:46.180 align:middle line:84%
of people, boys,
girls, men and women,

00:54:46.180 --> 00:54:48.990 align:middle line:90%
teens who are addicted to food.

